Language: en

00:00:00.089 --> 00:00:06.220
In the past five years, USB-C has become the
go-to connector for a wide range of devices.

00:00:06.220 --> 00:00:12.050
It’s used on most android phones, notebooks,
tablets, game consoles, headphones, and even

00:00:12.050 --> 00:00:15.929
accessories like mice, keyboards, and external
storage drives.

00:00:15.929 --> 00:00:22.260
But when it comes to Apple’s most popular
product, the iPhone, USB-C has yet to be adopted.

00:00:22.260 --> 00:00:26.960
Instead, every model of iPhone still uses
a Lightning connector that was introduced

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:29.539
eight years ago with the iPhone 5.

00:00:29.539 --> 00:00:34.829
This has led people to wonder why Apple hasn’t
transitioned the iPhone to USB-C, especially

00:00:34.829 --> 00:00:39.650
for a company who has a reputation of being
the first to adopt new standards.

00:00:39.650 --> 00:00:43.940
So in this video, I’m going to explain why
Apple hasn’t transitioned the iPhone to

00:00:43.940 --> 00:00:46.879
USB-C, and what that means for their users.

00:00:46.879 --> 00:00:51.210
This is Greg with Apple Explained, and you
guys voted this topic into second place in

00:00:51.210 --> 00:00:52.210
the last poll.

